As a condition of licensure, each hospital shall establish a utilization review program for all patients admitted to the hospital. The utilization review program:
May be conducted by an independent, nonhospital-affiliated review agent;
Shall be performed by registered nurses, medical records technicians, or similar qualified personnel supported and supervised by physicians as may be required;
Shall be certified by the Secretary if the program meets the minimum standards established under paragraph (4) of this subsection; and
Shall be recertified by the Secretary if the hospital makes any changes to the program after the initial certification.

The Secretary shall, by regulation and in consultation with health care providers and payors, establish minimum standards for a utilization review program, directed at appropriateness and quality of inpatient care, as enumerated in the following items:
Preadmission review of elective admissions;
Postadmission review of emergency admissions;
Concurrent or retrospective review of all admissions as appropriate;
Preauthorization of certain selected procedures if proposed to be performed on an inpatient basis;
Continued stay review based on recognized objective criteria;
Discharge planning review; and
Readmission review.

The Secretary shall, by regulation and in consultation with hospitals, physicians, interested community and advocacy groups, and representatives of the Maryland Defense Bar and Plaintiffs' Bar establish minimum standards for a risk management program which shall include:
A board policy statement indicating commitment to the risk management program;
A requirement that one person be assigned the responsibility for coordinating the program;
An internal staff committee structure to conduct ongoing review and evaluation of risk management activities;
A formal written program for addressing patient complaints;
A documented facility-wide risk reporting system;
Ongoing risk management education programs for all staff; and
Documentation that the risk management and quality assurance programs share relevant information.

The review of care shall:
Be undertaken for cases chosen at random and for cases with unexpected adverse outcomes;
Be based on objective review standards;
Include a review of the appropriateness of the plan of care for the patient, particularly any medical procedures performed on the patient, in relation to the patient's condition; and
